Below is a **complete, self‑contained design** for an OCaml binding to the C++ `libpcapng` iterator.  
It contains

* the public OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`);
* a tiny helper `pcapng.ml` that only registers the primitives (so the library can be built with `ocamlopt`);
* the C++ stub file (`pcapng_stubs.cpp`) that bridges the C++ iterator to OCaml and implements the callback‑style `iter`/`fold` functions.

The code is deliberately written with the classic OCaml C‑API (no `ctypes`) so it can be compiled with the normal OCaml tool‑chain and linked against a C++ library.

---

## 1.  Public OCaml interface – `pcapng.mli`

```ocaml
(** {1 libpcapng OCaml bindings} *)

(** A handle to an opened pcapng file.  The value is abstract – it is
    managed by the C++ side and freed automatically when the OCaml
    value is garbage‑collected. *)
type t

(** Information about a single captured frame.  All fields are copied
    out of the C++ structure, so the OCaml value does not keep any
    reference to the underlying C++ memory. *)
type frame = {
  ts      : float;      (** timestamp, seconds since epoch (fractional part) *)
  caplen  : int;        (** number of bytes actually captured *)
  origlen : int;        (** original length of the packet on the wire *)
  data    : bytes;      (** the captured bytes; length = [caplen] *)
}

(** Raised when the C++ library reports an error (e.g. file not found,
    malformed file, I/O error).  The payload is the human readable
    message returned by libpcapng. *)
exception Error of string

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.
    @raise Error if the file cannot be opened or parsed. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a handle explicitly.  The handle is also closed automatically
    by the finaliser, but calling [close] early can be useful to release
    the underlying file descriptor.  After calling [close] the handle
    must not be used again. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over all frames in the file and apply [f] to each of them.
    The iteration stops as soon as [f] raises an exception; the exception
    propagates to the caller.  The callback runs in the OCaml runtime,
    so it may allocate, raise, etc.  The iterator itself runs in C++,
    therefore it is fast and does not allocate OCaml values until a
    frame is actually delivered to the callback. *)
val iter : (frame -> unit) -> t -> unit

(** Fold over all frames.  The function [f] receives the current
    accumulator and the next frame and returns a new accumulator.
    The fold stops early if [f] raises. *)
val fold : ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> t -> 'a

(** Convenience: collect all frames into a list (useful for tests,
    debugging or small files). *)
val to_list : t -> frame list
```

---

## 2.  Tiny implementation – `pcapng.ml`

```ocaml
(* The .ml file only registers the primitives.  All the heavy lifting
   lives in the C++ stub. *)

external open_file : string -> t = "pcapng_open_file"
external close     : t -> unit   = "pcapng_close"

external iter      : (frame -> unit) -> t -> unit = "pcapng_iter"
external fold      : ('a -> frame -> 'a) -> 'a -> t -> 'a = "pcapng_fold"
external to_list   : t -> frame list = "pcapng_to_list"
```

